<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Purdypog</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Oct 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Sudedor sorry for the tone of my previous message.  I did take it in context, but I do not agree with the underlying assumption that there are times when slow is near worthless (except perhaps when an enchanter pet is tanking).  In all other cases, even in 30 second fights I can't imagine a better use of mana than slowing for a shaman as long as you can slow somewhat early in the encounter.<br />
<br />
It has been my experience in tipt, vxed etc. that even if you have a really tough tank and a competent cleric that 1) the cleric constantly runs low on mana even with a shaman slowing on incoming and keeping Q on the tank 2) the cleric is unable to safely use ch without a slow because the mob might get a lucky quad in.<br />
<br />
I suppose that if you substitute a second cleric for a shaman and the clerics only use their GoD fast heal and alternate medding then it would work fine (and probably be safer), but you would lose shaman utility and dps as a tradeoff for that safety.<br />
<br />
But anyway, I continue to think that our slow is not worthless even with mitigation because it allows a single cleric to do 90% of the healing thru their efficient ch and not run out of mana in a fast pulling group.  Also, its all about burst damage for shorter fights because without the burst damage Shaman fall significantly short in most encounters vs beastlords.  Additionally, we need burst damage because we Shaman do not want to become buffing bots which would happen if most of our damage is thru indirect longer duration buffing.<br />
<br />
Purdy</p>
	
	
	
	
	
